The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, July 15, 2004 				 Exide to ramp up capacity
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 (From left to right) Exide MD and COO T. V. Ramanathan, CEO S. B. Ganguly and non-executive director Bhaskar Mitter in Calcutta on Wednesday. Picture by Kishor Roy Chowdhury																								Calcutta, July 14: Exide Industries Ltd (EIL) will invest over Rs 60 crore to ramp up capacity of its automotive and industrial battery segments.																								While the automotive segment will get Rs 40 crore to increase production from 4.8 million to 5.5 million units per annum, Rs 20 crore would be invested at the companys traction battery plants in Haldia, Hosur and Taloja. 																								The capital expenditure will help the company raise its market share phenomenally in the next few years.																								Automotive battery contributes around Rs 800 crore sales while the total market size is about Rs 1,500 crore.																								Exide chairman S. B. Ganguly said both automotive and industrial battery segments will be further strengthened in the coming years.																								He also pointed out that the company will change the product portfolio of its submarine business. 																								The company, which repaid about Rs 170 crore debt last fiscal, would repay loans worth Rs 50 crore this year. The loan repayment has improved the debt-equity ratio from 1.43:1 two years ago to a healthy 0.62:1 now.																								Exide is planning to tap the Russian market for its submarine batteries. It will sign an agreement with the Russian navy for this. The Russians had visited the companys facilities and were satisfied with the quality of batteries, Ganguly said.																								Exide has posted a net profit of Rs 18.4 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2004 compared with Rs 13.86 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. Total income has increased to Rs 276.52 crore during the period under review from Rs 232.71 crore in the year-ago period. 
